snippet.textDisplay:
Just to clarify, "SARS-related coronaviruses" include the archetypal SARS virus of 2003 and SARS-like viruses found in bats and small mammals with obscure names most people have never heard of. Lab research is done on thousands of viruses to study their structure and identify areas where treatment or a vaccine could be of use.
There's nothing to indicate about SARS CoV 2 that it was artificial. There's plenty of studies right now in the American Journal of Virology, The Lancet, and EID that indicate it was not a big jump from SARS-related CoVs in humans and bats to SARS CoV 2.

snippet.textDisplay:
@James Karukayil 
You're not the one that needs "convincing". Coronaviruses have been known for decades before SARS. I am NOT referring to MERS CoV. MERS CoV operates in a slightly different way to the SARS subgroup viruses. Seriously, you sound like you just started researching this after this latest pandemic. 
You say "Spanish flu was the major zoonotic disease outbreak from mammals in human history"
First, what the hell does that mean. Are you saying "the only"?? If so you are wrong. HIV has heritage in SIV in our closest primate relatives. There are a number of pandemic influenzas that have zoonotic origin, not just the 1918 flu.

snippet.textDisplay:
@James Karukayil 
Wrong. SARS was the first serious human coronavirus outbreak jumped from mammals, but there are other coronaviruses that affect humans and cause upper respiratory infections and rarely lower (common cold). Several CoVs cause this picture in humans. Virologists were able to identify SARS virus as a coronavirus based on it's structure which they were already familiar with.
